  "explanation": "### Name\n- 〜んです／のです（説明・理由）\n\n### Meaning and function\n- Adds an explanatory or justificatory tone: the speaker is giving background, a reason, or clarifying the situation\n- In questions, gently asks for an explanation or confirmation rather than just a fact\n- Softens refusals, requests, and statements by presenting them as circumstance-based\n\n### Form and templates\n- Core\n  - V(dict/ない/た/なかった) + んです\n  - い-adj(〜い/〜くない/〜かった/〜くなかった) + んです\n  - な-adj + なんです／じゃないんです／だったんです／じゃなかったんです\n  - N + なんです／じゃないんです／だったんです／じゃなかったんです\n- Plain (non-polite) endings\n  - V/い-adj + んだ\n  - な-adj/N + なんだ\n- Questions\n  - … んですか ／ のですか（more formal/stiffer）\n  - Casual: … の?（soft/informal）\n- Softening lead-ins\n  - … んですが／んですけど + [request, offer, advice, follow-up]\n- Particle and ordering notes\n  - んです attaches to a plain-form clause; do not put です／ます before んです\n  - With N/な-adj, use な before の／ん (N/な-adj + な + の／ん)\n- Conjugation/inflection\n  - Negatives and past are formed in the clause before んです as shown above\n  - Common contractions: のです → んです (spoken); では → じゃ (casual)\n\n### Usage notes and constraints\n- Register/naturalness\n  - んです is very common and natural in conversation\n  - のです sounds more formal, explanatory, or literary; used in careful speech and writing\n  - んだ (plain) is stronger/blunter than んです; use with care depending on relationship and context\n- Semantics/scope\n  - Signals “there is a reason/background I’m sharing” or “please explain” (in questions)\n  - Often implies shared context, concern, or justification; not for neutral definitions or universal facts\n  - Frequently used to soften refusals, give context before a request, or clarify new/contrasting info\n- Questions with んですか\n  - Softer and more “why/how come?” in feel than a bare factual question\n  - Without context, can sound prying; add hedges or context in polite situations\n- Orthographic/variant notes\n  - んです is the colloquial contraction of のです\n  - じゃ (casual) ↔ では (formal) before ない／なかった with N/な-adj\n  - Casual sentence-final の? can sound soft/friendly; use only in informal contexts\n\n### Common mistakes (optional, only if relevant)\n- Using だんです with N/な-adj; correct is なんです／なんだ\n- Putting ます／です before んです (e.g., Vますんです); the clause before んです must be in plain form\n- Forgetting な before の／ん with N/な-adj (N/な-adj + なのです／なんです)\n- Adding な after い-adjectives (い-adj + な + んです is incorrect)\n- Overusing んです in formal writing or with objective statements where no explanation is intended\n\n### Related grammar (optional, only if relevant)\n- 〜から／〜ので: Explicit “because.” ので is softer/more formal; んです is explanatory tone rather than a direct cause connector\n- 〜わけです: “It means that…” logical conclusion/summary; more objective than the speaker-centered んです\n- 〜の (sentence-final): Casual explanatory/confirming tone; informal counterpart of んです\n- 〜んですが／〜んですけど …: Explanatory lead-in commonly used to soften or prepare a request or proposal",
